docs.abstract: Officers in riot gear cleared the makeshift camp in City Hall Park, which began as a protest against police abuses but then turned into a gathering of homeless people.
docs.snippet: Officers in riot gear cleared the makeshift camp in City Hall Park, which began as a protest against police abuses but then turned into a gathering of homeless people.
docs.lead_paragraph: Police officers in riot gear cleared out the “Occupy City Hall” encampment in City Hall Park near dawn on Wednesday, shutting down a monthlong demonstration against police brutality that recently had attracted numerous homeless people.

headline.main: ‘Occupy City Hall’ Encampment Taken Down in Pre-Dawn Raid by N.Y.P.D.
headline.print_headline: New York Police Push Out ‘Occupy City Hall’ Camp in Predawn Raid

byline.original: By Alan Feuer and Juliana Kim

docs.abstract: On a road trip to Detroit, reflections on the car as a symbol of aspiration and adventure. But if you’re Black in America, that lovely machine isn’t always a refuge.
docs.snippet: On a road trip to Detroit, reflections on the car as a symbol of aspiration and adventure. But if you’re Black in America, that lovely machine isn’t always a refuge.
docs.lead_paragraph: Driving across Woodward Avenue in Detroit a few weeks ago amid a spirited George Floyd demonstration — this one a 30-mile motorcade into the suburbs, billed as the “I Have a Dream Protest Cruise” — my mind drifted strangely to an empty two-lane highway in Arkansas near the Texas border. The memory was jarring, sweeping me away from this raucous caravan — honking horns, Black-power fists thrust from car windows, the whir of sirens — back to my youth in the spring of 1986.

docs.abstract: The comic is a leading figure in the country’s stand-up scene, known for confronting issues of discrimination and identity. Recently, though, being funny has taken a back seat.
docs.snippet: The comic is a leading figure in the country’s stand-up scene, known for confronting issues of discrimination and identity. Recently, though, being funny has taken a back seat.
docs.lead_paragraph: PARIS — As news of George Floyd’s killing by the police ricocheted around the world last month, the French stand-up comedian Fary Lopes, known as Fary, wasn’t telling jokes.

headline.main: Fary Isn’t Joking About Race in France Right Now
headline.print_headline: French Comic Evolves Faster Than France

docs.abstract: This incipient movement risks being reduced to a fleeting instant of heightened consciousness.
docs.snippet: This incipient movement risks being reduced to a fleeting instant of heightened consciousness.
docs.lead_paragraph: Since George Floyd’s murder, America has begun a remarkable reckoning with racial injustice. People of every race and generation have come together in largely peaceful protests across the nation to halt police brutality, which is disproportionately directed at people of color. But many Americans are demanding much more — that we finally redress the systemic racism that persists in this country, understanding that it diminishes us all.

headline.main: Take the Next Step Toward Racial Justice
headline.print_headline: Take the Next Step Toward Racial Justice

docs.abstract: Secoriea Turner, 8, was one of several children killed across the country over the holiday weekend. Her death has roiled Atlanta.
docs.snippet: Secoriea Turner, 8, was one of several children killed across the country over the holiday weekend. Her death has roiled Atlanta.
docs.lead_paragraph: ATLANTA — Activists with Black Lives Matter had a vision for what the scorched remains of a Wendy’s restaurant could become: the Rayshard Brooks Peace Center, a gathering place in Atlanta with job training, counseling and youth programs that would be a living memorial named for the man whose fatal encounter with the police transformed the fast-food eatery into the heart of the city’s turmoil.

headline.main: ‘It’s Got to Stop’: Atlanta’s Mayor Decries a Surge of Violence as a Girl Is Killed
headline.print_headline: Atlanta Mayor Deplores Violence: ‘It Has to Stop’

docs.abstract: Many Latinos are pushing for an acknowledgment of the systemic racism they face, and a conversation about over-policing in their own communities.
docs.snippet: Many Latinos are pushing for an acknowledgment of the systemic racism they face, and a conversation about over-policing in their own communities.
docs.lead_paragraph: PHOENIX — “Tu lucha es mi lucha,” several signs declared at a recent Black Lives Matter protest near the Arizona State Capitol. Your struggle is my struggle. The sea of faces included young Latinos who had marched before, during the immigrant rights movement in the state a decade ago, when Joe Arpaio championed draconian policies as the sheriff of Maricopa County. There was no doubt in these protesters’ minds: Their fights against racism are bound up together.

headline.main: Latinos Back Black Lives Matter Protests. They Want Change for Themselves, Too.
headline.print_headline: Latinos Seek Voice in Black-and-White Dialogue

docs.abstract: Players and coaches knelt before the national anthem, and teams played a message of unity at the first two games of the 2020 season.
docs.snippet: Players and coaches knelt before the national anthem, and teams played a message of unity at the first two games of the 2020 season.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The 200-yard black cloth stretched along the foul lines, starting at one edge of the outfield, wrapping around home plate and extending to the other side of the diamond. It was held by coaches and players from both the Washington Nationals and the Yankees, all spaced out, as a message recorded by the actor Morgan Freeman played over the stadium speakers.

headline.main: On Opening Day, a Rarity for M.L.B.: Support for Black Lives Matter
headline.print_headline: Baseball, Latecomer on Social Issues, Honors Black Lives Matter on Opening Day

docs.abstract: A new court filing says Ms. Taylor, whose death set off protests, received no medical help after she was shot by the police. The coroner asserts that her injuries were so severe she could not have been saved.
docs.snippet: A new court filing says Ms. Taylor, whose death set off protests, received no medical help after she was shot by the police. The coroner asserts that her injuries were so severe she could not have been saved.
docs.lead_paragraph: LOUISVILLE, Ky. — For up to six minutes after she was shot by police officers during a drug raid, Breonna Taylor, an emergency room technician, lay dying in her apartment but received no medical aid, her family claims in a new court filing.

headline.main: Breonna Taylor’s Family Claims She Was Alive After Shooting but Given No Aid
headline.print_headline: Family Asserts That Louisville Victim Got No Aid After Police Shot Her

docs.abstract: “We must have a new sense of urgency to make this declaration,” Mayor Greg Fischer said. The city has been the focus of protests after the police killing of Breonna Taylor.
docs.snippet: “We must have a new sense of urgency to make this declaration,” Mayor Greg Fischer said. The city has been the focus of protests after the police killing of Breonna Taylor.
docs.lead_paragraph: Officials in Louisville, Ky., where there have been continuing protests over the police killing of Breonna Taylor and where coronavirus cases have begun to rise, said on Wednesday that the city might join a growing list of local governments that have declared racism a public health crisis.

headline.main: Louisville May Become Latest City to Declare Racism a Public Health Crisis

docs.abstract: The pandemic has been brutal to buskers. It’s even harder when you have to haul a Steinway all over New York City.
docs.snippet: The pandemic has been brutal to buskers. It’s even harder when you have to haul a Steinway all over New York City.
docs.lead_paragraph: Colin Huggins, the piano man of Washington Square Park, sat at his Steinway baby grand the other day playing one of Claude Debussy’s frolicking arabesques. A few onlookers wore surgical masks and listened from benches. Elsewhere in the park, a Black Lives Matter protest was starting and a worker climbed up a ladder to scrub away graffiti from the Washington Arch.

headline.main: It’s a Tough Time to Be a Street Musician With a 900-Pound Piano
headline.print_headline: Hard Times for the Piano Man of Washington Sq. Park

byline.original: By Alex Vadukul and September Dawn Bottoms
